<TITLE> European stocks in sea of red, track global losses </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, July 26 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European shares extended losses in late trade on Thursday, suffering their biggest daily decline in more than four months, hit by a deteriorating climate for financing takeovers and concerns about US housing. By 1515 GMT, the pan-European FTSEurofirst 300 index had dropped 2.3 percent to 1,534.6, the day's low and its weakest level since April 12. The index fell for the third day in a row. The FTSEurofirst 300 index has lost 6 percent since hitting a 6-1/2-year high of 1,635.6 on July 13, but is still up nearly 4 percent so far this year. Banks were among the biggest drags on the index with Royal Bank of Scotland, Credit Suisse and UBS down between 2.8 and 3.4 percent. US stock indexes took a beating on signs of further detioration in the housing market, higher oil prices and financing worries. The Dow and Nasdaq were both down 1.3 percent. U.S. Treasuries rall
